==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*bīben-'', from Indo-European ''*bhoyə-'' ‘be frightened’.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[bivia]], Old Saxon [[biƀon|biƀōn]] (Dutch [[beven]]), Old High German [[bibēn]] (German [[beben]]), Old Norse [[bifa]] (Swedish [[bäva]])

''Indo-European cognates:'' Slavic ''*bōyātī'' (Old Church Slavonic [[боти сѩ]], Russian [[бояться]], Polish [[bać się]]), Baltic ''*baida-'' (Lithuanian [[baidas]])

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'bɪvian/

===Verb===
'''bifian''' (class 2 weak)
# to [[shiver]] or [[tremble]]
#:''He, bifiende, feoll to Iohannes fotum'': he fell, trembling, at John's feet.  (Ælfric)

